{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_017M18Dvfkm21ZYaxHCGzKPs","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package spring.tutorial.roster;\n     2→\n     3→import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\n     4→import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;\n     5→import org.springframework.boot.test.context.SpringBootTest;\n     6→import spring.tutorial.roster.request.Request;\n     7→import spring.tutorial.roster.util.LeagueDetails;\n     8→import spring.tutorial.roster.util.TeamDetails;\n     9→\n    10→import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertEquals;\n    11→\n    12→@SpringBootTest\n    13→class RequestSmokeTest {\n    14→\n    15→  @Autowired\n    16→  Request request;\n    17→\n    18→  @Test\n    19→  void roundTrip() {\n    20→    request.createLeague(new LeagueDetails(\"L1\",\"Summer Fun\",\"soccer\"));\n    21→    request.createTeamInLeague(new TeamDetails(\"T1\",\"Tigers\",\"Austin\"), \"L1\");\n    22→    request.createPlayer(\"P1\",\"Alice\",\"Forward\",100000);\n    23→    request.addPlayer(\"P1\",\"T1\");\n    24→    assertEquals(1, request.getPlayersOfTeam(\"T1\").size());\n    25→  }\n    26→}\n    27→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01YMeKSn1LMs6a2XPagvW9SA","session_id":"9a37b03b-5080-41c1-93e0-db6136171128","uuid":"59ac490a-f7d5-43ba-ba53-56d5719dda58"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01YMeKSn1LMs6a2XPagvW9SA","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Note: There's a typo in the filename (RequestSmokeText,java instead of RequestSmokeTest.java), which might cause issues.\n\nI'll summarize the key observations:\n\n1. This is a Spring Boot application for managing a sports roster system\n2. Uses H2 in-memory database\n3. Supports creating Leagues (Summer and Winter), Teams, and Players\n4. Implements complex queries for players across different dimensions\n5. Uses Spring Data JPA for repository operations\n6. Includes unit and integration tests\n7. Supports REST API endpoints for all operations\n\nThe application is well-structured with:\n- Entity classes in `jakartaee.tutorial.roster.entity`\n- Repositories in `spring.tutorial.roster.repository`\n- Request handling in `spring.tutorial.roster.request`\n- REST controllers in `spring.tutorial.roster.rest`\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of the codebase?"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9a37b03b-5080-41c1-93e0-db6136171128","uuid":"731a7b1f-5d03-4d04-be08-af4ba353b545"}
